ix tuning whiskers along the winch core’s upper flange and plant the airflow chime behind a prayer scroll rack.\", \"Copy the pressure-vector inscriptions chalked by senior Chainwardens and photograph them using Istel’s skyglass coin.\", \"Exit across the chainhouse catwalk and use the glide harness to reach the neighboring lantern tower without being seen.\"],\n  \"dialogue\": [\n    {\"speaker\": \"Erynn Sythar\", \"lines\": \"You’ve danced along the Cathedral’s ribs before, but you never listened the way I need you to now, Lyris. The chain has a pulse the hymn hides, a faint tremor that slips between the choir’s cadences, and the whiskers I’ve built will taste that tremor like a tongue tastes salt on the wind. The chime is a heresy and a promise together; it will tease eddies into speech and let our receivers pull meaning from the breath behind the prayers. Bring me numbers, not heroics, because numbers will argue for us in chambers where no one will let us sing, and numbers will tell us which knot to loosen and which to leave bound. If you are seen, you are a thief; if you are heard, you are a blasphemy; if you are felt, you are a gust the Wardens will wall off with law. Go in as a subtraction that leaves no remainder, and when the Crown of Cirrus comes back around, we will have a stanza of the Old Song written in figures even the Hinge must respect.\"},\n    {\"speaker\": \"Lyris Kael\", \"lines\": \"Numbers I can carry, and I can wear silence like a cloak; heroics go clang and stain the floor where oaths keep score. I know the choir’s breath and the timing of the ratchets, and I know where the stained glass throws blind light across the trusses so a shadow becomes a sermon no one remembers hearing. I will plant your whiskers where the tremor lives and leave the chime to whisper behind scripture, and I will copy the chalk marks the senior Wardens adore as if they were commandments carved in iron. If the chain speaks in the tongue you believe it has, we will hea